Text:
To create a graph using Mermaid.js syntax based on your requirements, we first need to organize the data into entities, attributes, relations, goals, conditions, and decision variables. Then, we'll structure them according to the specified connections and color coding.

Here's how you can represent this in Mermaid.js Live Editor:

```mermaid
graph TD

    // Define Entities (in blue)
    subgraph Entity1[Entity1]
        style Entity1 fill:#blue,stroke-width:2px,color:white;
    end
    
    subgraph Entity2[Entity2]
        style Entity2 fill:#blue,stroke-width:2px,color:white;
    end

    // Define Attributes (in white)
    A1(Attribute1 of Entity1) --> Entity1
    A2(Attribute2 of Entity1) --> Entity1
    A3(Attribute1 of Entity2) --> Entity2
    
    // Define Relations (in orange)
    R1[Relation1] -->|Entity1 to Entity2| Entity2
    style R1 fill:#orange,stroke-width:2px,color:white;
    
    // Define Goals (in green)
    G1[Goal1] --> Entity1
    G2[Goal2] --> A3
    
    // Define Conditions (in red)
    C1[Condition1] --> Entity2
    C2[Condition2] --> A1

    // Define Decision Variables (in purple)
    DV1[DecisionVar1] --> Entity1
    style DV1 fill:#purple,stroke-width:2px,color:white;

```

### Explanation:

- **Entities**: Represented as subgraphs with a blue color.
- **Attributes**: Listed and connected to their respective entities. They are in white.
- **Relations**: Shown as separate nodes connecting entities, colored orange.
- **Goals**: Connected to entities or attributes, colored green.
- **Conditions**: Linked to entities or attributes, colored red.
- **Decision Variables**: Associated with relevant entities, colored purple.

### Notes:

1. Adjust the entity names (`Entity1`, `Entity2`) and attribute names (`Attribute1`, etc.) as per your actual data.
2. Add more subgraphs for additional entities if needed.
3. Modify connections to reflect real-world relationships in your dataset.
4. You can customize node styles further if necessary.

This setup will create a visual representation of the data structure you described, using Mermaid.js syntax.
